Use a fixed date for e.g. March and you will see that the test is not passing anymore.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 16, 8, 56, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'm-herold', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 426227161, 'comment_body': 'From August 1st to August 31st, this test would still be passing, although the function could wrongly return a full version of the month name (e.g., "LLL**L** d, yyyy"). Using a hard-coded date will make this function much error-prone and also more readable:

```
let newYearsDay2020 = NSDate(timeIntervalSince1970: 1577844000)
XCTAssertEqual(kLocalizedJan + " 1, 2020", newYearsDay2020.humanFriendlyFormattedString())
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 17, 7, 18, 1, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'm-herold', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 426227400, 'comment_body': "I would recommend to remove those deprecated arrays, since this can be done using Swift's standard functionality (e.g., using date formatters).", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 17, 7, 20, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'm-herold', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 426227434, 'comment_body': 'Do not use them outside the extension, move them inside the extension and convert to non-optional computed properties.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 17, 7, 21, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'm-herold', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 426227464, 'comment_body': 'Why not using `LLL d, yyyy` here directly?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 17, 7, 21, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'm-herold', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 426240601, 'comment_body': "In order to make the tests independent of the operating system's language, please change to `kLocalizedToday` and `kLocalizedYesterday` below.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 17, 9, 50, 32, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'm-herold', 'type': 'User'}]
